<exercise id="fs-id1493327" type="problems-exercises"><problem id="fs-id1145418">
    <para id="import-auto-id2010563">A marathon runner completes a <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mtext>42</m:mtext><m:mtext>.</m:mtext><m:mtext>188</m:mtext><m:mtext>-km</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{"42" "." "188""-km"} {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> course in <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>2</m:mn><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:mtext>h</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{2" h"} {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>, 30 min, and <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mtext>12</m:mtext><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:mtext>s</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{"12"" s"} {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>. There is an uncertainty of <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mtext>25</m:mtext><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:mtext>m</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{"25"" m"} {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> in the distance traveled and an uncertainty of 1 s in the elapsed time. (a) Calculate the percent uncertainty in the distance. (b) Calculate the uncertainty in the elapsed time. (c) What is the average speed in meters per second? (d) What is the uncertainty in the average speed?</para></problem></exercise>
<exercise id="fs-id2509052" type="problems-exercises"><problem id="fs-id2733260">
    <para id="import-auto-id1335200">The sides of a small rectangular box are measured to be <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>1</m:mn><m:mtext>.</m:mtext><m:mrow><m:mtext>80</m:mtext><m:mo stretchy="false">±</m:mo><m:mn>0</m:mn></m:mrow><m:mtext>.</m:mtext><m:mtext>01</m:mtext><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:mtext>cm</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{1 "." "80" +- 0 "." "01"" cm"} {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>, <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow/><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0">{}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math><m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>2</m:mn><m:mtext>.</m:mtext><m:mrow><m:mtext>05</m:mtext><m:mo stretchy="false">±</m:mo><m:mn>0</m:mn></m:mrow><m:mtext>.</m:mtext><m:mtext>02</m:mtext><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:mtext>cm, and 3</m:mtext><m:mtext>.</m:mtext><m:mrow><m:mn>1</m:mn><m:mo stretchy="false">±</m:mo><m:mn>0</m:mn></m:mrow><m:mtext>.</m:mtext><m:mtext>1 cm</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{2 "." "05" +- 0 "." "02"" cm, and 3" "." 1 +- 0 "." "1 cm"} {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> long. Calculate its volume and uncertainty in cubic centimeters.</para></problem>
<solution id="fs-id3081865">
    <para id="import-auto-id1538038"><m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mtext>11</m:mtext><m:mo stretchy="false">±</m:mo><m:mn>1</m:mn></m:mrow><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:msup><m:mtext>cm</m:mtext><m:mrow><m:mn>3</m:mn></m:mrow></m:msup></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{"11" +- 1" cm" rSup { size 8{3} } } {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math></para></solution></exercise>
<exercise id="fs-id2560910" type="problems-exercises"><problem id="fs-id1598812">
    <para id="import-auto-id1514014">When non-metric units were used in the United Kingdom, a unit of mass called the <emphasis effect="italics"><emphasis effect="italics">pound-mass</emphasis></emphasis> (lbm) was employed, where <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>1</m:mn><m:mrow><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:mtext>lbm</m:mtext><m:mo stretchy="false">=</m:mo><m:mn>0</m:mn></m:mrow><m:mtext>.</m:mtext><m:mtext>4539</m:mtext><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:mtext>kg</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{1" lbm"=0 "." "4539"`"kg"} {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>. (a) If there is an uncertainty of <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>0</m:mn><m:mtext>.</m:mtext><m:mtext>0001</m:mtext><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:mtext>kg</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{0 "." "0001"`"kg"} {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> in the pound-mass unit, what is its percent uncertainty? (b) Based on that percent uncertainty, what mass in pound-mass has an uncertainty of 1 kg when converted to kilograms?</para></problem></exercise>
<exercise id="fs-id2637086" type="problems-exercises"><problem id="fs-id2996423">
    <para id="import-auto-id1553348">The length and width of a rectangular room are measured to be <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>3</m:mn><m:mtext>.</m:mtext><m:mrow><m:mtext>955</m:mtext><m:mo stretchy="false">±</m:mo><m:mn>0</m:mn></m:mrow><m:mtext>.</m:mtext><m:mtext>005</m:mtext><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:mtext>m</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{3 "." "955" +- 0 "." "005"" m"} {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math> and <m:math><m:semantics><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>3</m:mn><m:mtext>.</m:mtext><m:mrow><m:mtext>050</m:mtext><m:mo stretchy="false">±</m:mo><m:mn>0</m:mn></m:mrow><m:mtext>.</m:mtext><m:mtext>005</m:mtext><m:mspace width="0.25em"/><m:mtext> m</m:mtext></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow><m:annotation encoding="StarMath 5.0"> size 12{3 "." "050" +- 0 "." "005"" m"} {}</m:annotation></m:semantics></m:math>. Calculate the area of the room and its uncertainty in square meters.</para></problem>
